// irrational_constants.test.gg -- Periodic Table of Irrationals
//
// Maps every major mathematical irrational constant to the five-primitive
// framework (FORK, RACE, FOLD, SLIVER, VENT).  For each constant:
//   1. What it is (which primitive it governs)
//   2. WHY it is irrational (what property of the primitives requires it)
//   3. How it connects to phi
//   4. Status: PROVED, CONJECTURED, or REFRAMED
//
// Thesis: each major irrational governs one primitive or one transition.
// Together they form the periodic table of irrationals.
//
// Numeric ordering of the primary five:
//   sqrt(2) < phi < sqrt(3) < e < pi
//   1.414   < 1.618 < 1.732 < 2.718 < 3.141
//   FOLD    < SLIVER < RACE < VENT < FORK

(test_suite: TestSuite { name: 'irrational-constants' })


// ============================================================================
// I. phi = (1 + sqrt(5)) / 2 = 1.61803398...
//    THE SLIVER CONSTANT -- Status: PROVED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: phi is the eigenvalue of SLIVER.  Constructive interference
// scales amplitude by phi; destructive scales by 1/phi = phi - 1.  The
// Fibonacci recurrence F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2) is discrete constructive
// interference and its ratio converges to phi.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: If phi were rational p/q, interference patterns would
// repeat with period q.  Irrationality guarantees interference never fully
// resolves -- always a residual, always a next term.  phi is the "most
// irrational" number (hardest to approximate by rationals) because
// interference must maximally avoid periodic lock-in.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: phi is phi.  Identity.

(phi_source: Constant {
  name: 'phi', value: '1.61803398875',
  formula: '(1 + sqrt(5)) / 2',
  primitive: 'SLIVER', status: 'PROVED'
})

(phi_fib_a: Scalar { value: '1.0' })
(phi_fib_b: Scalar { value: '1.0' })
(phi_interference: Interference { mode: 'constructive', eigenvalue: '1.61803398875' })
(phi_ratio: Ratio { expect: '1.61803398875', tolerance: '0.001' })

(phi_fib_a)-[:SLIVER { mode: 'constructive' }]->(phi_fib_b)
(phi_fib_b)-[:PROCESS]->(phi_interference)
(phi_interference)-[:PROCESS]->(phi_ratio)

// Destructive complement: 1/phi = phi - 1 = 0.618...
(phi_destructive: Interference { mode: 'destructive', eigenvalue: '0.61803398875' })
(phi_fib_a)-[:SLIVER { mode: 'destructive' }]->(phi_destructive)

(phi_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'phi is SLIVER eigenvalue: F(n)/F(n-1) -> phi',
  status: 'PROVED'
})


// ============================================================================
// II. pi = 3.14159265...
//     THE FORK CONSTANT -- Status: REFRAMED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: pi is the period constant of FORK.  When FORK creates branches with
// equal probability in all directions it produces radial symmetry -- a circle.
// pi = circumference / diameter.  1 picolorenzo = pi days.  pi governs
// oscillation, rotation, periodicity.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: If pi were rational the circle would close after finitely
// many steps and FORK would have finite distinguishable branches.  Irrationality
// (transcendence) ensures FORK's fan-out is genuinely continuous -- no smallest
// angular quantum, no lattice of allowed directions.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: pi / phi = 1.94161... (close to 2 but not equal).
// phi and pi are algebraically independent -- FORK and SLIVER are
// independent primitives.  But the Fibonacci spiral approximates a circle,
// so SLIVER converges toward FORK as interference steps grow.

(pi_source: Constant {
  name: 'pi', value: '3.14159265359',
  formula: 'circumference / diameter',
  primitive: 'FORK', status: 'REFRAMED'
})

// FORK creates radial symmetry -- equal probability in all directions
(pi_origin: Scalar { value: '1.0' })
(pi_branch_n: Branch { angle: '0', probability: '0.25' })
(pi_branch_e: Branch { angle: '1.5708', probability: '0.25' })
(pi_branch_s: Branch { angle: '3.14159', probability: '0.25' })
(pi_branch_w: Branch { angle: '4.71239', probability: '0.25' })

(pi_origin)-[:FORK]->(pi_branch_n | pi_branch_e | pi_branch_s | pi_branch_w)

// Circumference of unit circle = 2*pi
(pi_circumference: Metric { name: 'circumference', value: '6.28318', formula: '2 * pi' })
(pi_branch_n | pi_branch_e | pi_branch_s | pi_branch_w)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'sum-arc-length' }]->(pi_circumference)

// Oscillation: FORK drives periodicity with period 2*pi
(pi_oscillator: Oscillator { period: '6.28318', primitive: 'FORK' })
(pi_circumference)-[:PROCESS]->(pi_oscillator)

(pi_phi_ratio: Ratio {
  numerator: '3.14159', denominator: '1.61803', value: '1.94161',
  note: 'close to 2 but irrational -- FORK and SLIVER are independent'
})

(pi_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'pi governs FORK: radial symmetry implies circular period',
  status: 'REFRAMED'
})


// ============================================================================
// III. e = 2.71828182...
//      THE VENT CONSTANT -- Status: REFRAMED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: e is the growth/decay constant of VENT.  VENT sheds entropy
// proportional to current state: dN/dt = -lambda*N.  This proportionality
// is exponential decay and its base is e.  Landauer heat dissipates
// exponentially.  Half-life = ln(2)/lambda involves e.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: If e were rational, exponential decay would terminate
// in finite steps -- the system would reach exact zero.  Transcendence
// ensures VENT never fully completes: always a residual, always more
// entropy to shed.  VENT is the primitive that can never finish.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: e / phi = 1.67988... (close to 5/3).
// e^phi = 5.043... ~ 5 (the number of primitives).  CONJECTURED.

(e_source: Constant {
  name: 'e', value: '2.71828182846',
  formula: 'lim(1 + 1/n)^n as n -> inf',
  primitive: 'VENT', status: 'REFRAMED'
})

// VENT: proportional shedding models exponential decay
(e_initial: Scalar { value: '100.0' })
(e_step_1: Vent { rate: '0.5', base: 'e' })
(e_step_2: Vent { rate: '0.5', base: 'e' })
(e_step_3: Vent { rate: '0.5', base: 'e' })
(e_residual: Scalar { expect: '22.31', tolerance: '0.5' })

(e_initial)-[:VENT { lambda: '0.5' }]->(e_step_1)
(e_step_1)-[:VENT { lambda: '0.5' }]->(e_step_2)
(e_step_2)-[:VENT { lambda: '0.5' }]->(e_step_3)
(e_step_3)-[:PROCESS]->(e_residual)

// Landauer's bound: minimum energy to erase one bit = kT*ln(2)
(e_landauer: Metric {
  name: 'landauer_bound', formula: 'kT * ln(2)',
  note: 'minimum VENT cost per bit at temperature T'
})

// e^phi ~ 5.043 -- close to the number of primitives
(e_phi_exp: Ratio {
  formula: 'e^phi', value: '5.04316',
  note: 'e raised to SLIVER eigenvalue ~ number of primitives -- CONJECTURED'
})

(e_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'e governs VENT: proportional shedding requires exponential base',
  status: 'REFRAMED'
})


// ============================================================================
// IV. sqrt(2) = 1.41421356...
//     THE FOLD CONSTANT -- Status: REFRAMED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: sqrt(2) is the diagonal of the unit square -- what you get when you
// FOLD two equal things at right angles.  Pythagorean theorem: two unit vectors
// folded orthogonally produce magnitude sqrt(2).  The FOLD constant for
// symmetric inputs.  In the anti-Fibonacci sequence the eigenvalue magnitude
// involves sqrt(2).  Governs the NON-LINEAR regime.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: If sqrt(2) were rational p/q, the diagonal and side of a
// square would be commensurable.  But FOLD of two equal orthogonal things
// creates something genuinely new -- not expressible as a ratio of the inputs.
// The oldest known proof by contradiction (Hippasus) captures the essential
// property of FOLD: combining equal things produces incommensurable results.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: phi / sqrt(2) = 1.14412...  sqrt(2) < phi: FOLD constant
// is less than SLIVER constant.  Folding merely aggregates while
// interference creates resonance.

(sqrt2_source: Constant {
  name: 'sqrt(2)', value: '1.41421356237',
  formula: 'diagonal of unit square',
  primitive: 'FOLD', status: 'REFRAMED'
})

// FOLD: two equal orthogonal vectors produce sqrt(2) magnitude
(sqrt2_vec_x: Scalar { value: '1.0', direction: 'x' })
(sqrt2_vec_y: Scalar { value: '1.0', direction: 'y' })
(sqrt2_diagonal: Metric { name: 'diagonal', expect: '1.41421', tolerance: '0.001' })

(sqrt2_vec_x | sqrt2_vec_y)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'pythagorean' }]->(sqrt2_diagonal)

// The 1/3, 2/3 paper-cut ratio: 2/3 / 1/3 = 2 = sqrt(2)^2
(sqrt2_paper_a: Scalar { value: '0.333' })
(sqrt2_paper_b: Scalar { value: '0.667' })
(sqrt2_paper_ratio: Ratio { value: '2.0', note: 'sqrt(2)^2 = 2 -- squared FOLD constant' })
(sqrt2_paper_a | sqrt2_paper_b)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'ratio' }]->(sqrt2_paper_ratio)

// Anti-Fibonacci zigzag: eigenvalue in NON-LINEAR regime
(sqrt2_antifib_a: Scalar { value: '1.0' })
(sqrt2_antifib_b: Scalar { value: '-1.0' })
(sqrt2_zigzag: Interference {
  mode: 'destructive', eigenvalue: '-1.41421',
  note: 'anti-Fibonacci eigenvalue in NON-LINEAR regime'
})
(sqrt2_antifib_a)-[:SLIVER { mode: 'destructive' }]->(sqrt2_antifib_b)
(sqrt2_antifib_b)-[:PROCESS]->(sqrt2_zigzag)

// Hippasus proof: irrationality = FOLD incommensurability
(sqrt2_hippasus: Proof {
  method: 'contradiction', claim: 'sqrt(2) is irrational',
  implication: 'FOLD of equal orthogonal inputs is incommensurable', status: 'PROVED'
})

(sqrt2_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'sqrt(2) governs FOLD: Pythagorean diagonal of symmetric inputs',
  status: 'REFRAMED'
})


// ============================================================================
// V. sqrt(3) = 1.73205080...
//    THE RACE CONSTANT -- Status: CONJECTURED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: sqrt(3) is the height of the equilateral triangle -- the simplest
// geometry of a three-way RACE.  Three equal contestants produce equilateral
// symmetry; sqrt(3) is the fundamental ratio (height / half-base).
// Appears in: hexagonal close-packing, crystal lattices, three-body problem,
// 120-degree Steiner tree junctions.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: If sqrt(3) were rational, three equal contestants would
// have a commensurable meeting point.  Three-way symmetry cannot be reduced
// to a finite p/q because rational numbers are binary (numerator/denominator).
// A third contestant breaks binary commensurability.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: sqrt(3) / phi = 1.07039... (close to 1).  Three-way
// racing and two-way interference are "almost the same operation" at
// different arities.  The sequence sqrt(2), sqrt(3), sqrt(5) = phi + 1/phi
// interleaves primitive constants.

(sqrt3_source: Constant {
  name: 'sqrt(3)', value: '1.73205080757',
  formula: 'height of equilateral triangle',
  primitive: 'RACE', status: 'CONJECTURED'
})

// RACE: three equal contestants form equilateral symmetry
(sqrt3_racer_a: Racer { speed: '1.0', label: 'A' })
(sqrt3_racer_b: Racer { speed: '1.0', label: 'B' })
(sqrt3_racer_c: Racer { speed: '1.0', label: 'C' })
(sqrt3_height: Metric {
  name: 'triangle_height', value: '1.73205',
  formula: 'sqrt(3) * side / 2 where side = 2', tolerance: '0.001'
})

(sqrt3_racer_a | sqrt3_racer_b | sqrt3_racer_c)-[:RACE { expect: 'equilateral' }]->(sqrt3_height)

// Hexagonal packing: spacing governed by sqrt(3)
(sqrt3_hex_center: Node { position: '0,0' })
(sqrt3_hex_n1: Node { position: '1,0' })
(sqrt3_hex_n2: Node { position: '0.5,0.866' })
(sqrt3_hex_n3: Node { position: '-0.5,0.866' })
(sqrt3_hex_spacing: Metric {
  name: 'hex_row_spacing', value: '0.86603',
  formula: 'sqrt(3)/2', note: 'vertical distance between hexagonal rows'
})

(sqrt3_hex_center)-[:FORK]->(sqrt3_hex_n1 | sqrt3_hex_n2 | sqrt3_hex_n3)
(sqrt3_hex_n1 | sqrt3_hex_n2 | sqrt3_hex_n3)-[:RACE { expect: 'equidistant' }]->(sqrt3_hex_spacing)

// Steiner point: 120-degree optimal RACE network junction
(sqrt3_steiner: Metric {
  name: 'steiner_angle', value: '120', unit: 'degrees',
  note: 'optimal race-network junction angle involves sqrt(3)'
})

(sqrt3_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'sqrt(3) governs RACE: equilateral symmetry of three contestants',
  status: 'CONJECTURED'
})


// ============================================================================
// VI. ln(2) = 0.69314718...
//     THE VENT QUANTUM -- Status: PROVED (Landauer)
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: ln(2) is the minimum cost of one VENT operation.  Landauer's bound:
// erasing one bit requires dissipating at least kT*ln(2) joules.  This is
// thermodynamic law, not design choice.  ln(2) is the VENT quantum -- the
// smallest unit of forgetting.  Below this threshold information cannot be
// destroyed (only moved, which is FOLD not VENT).
// Half-life = ln(2)/lambda.  Doubling time = ln(2)/lambda.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: ln(2) = log_e(2).  If rational, e^(p/q) = 2 would make
// e algebraic, contradicting Hermite's transcendence proof.  The VENT
// constant (e) and the VENT quantum (ln(2)) are incommensurable.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: ln(2) / ln(phi) = log_phi(2) = 1.44042...
// It takes ~1.44 Fibonacci steps (phi-steps) to produce one doubling.
// The SLIVER-to-VENT conversion rate.

(ln2_source: Constant {
  name: 'ln(2)', value: '0.69314718056',
  formula: 'log_e(2)',
  primitive: 'VENT', role: 'quantum', status: 'PROVED'
})

// Landauer's bound: kT * ln(2) per bit erased
(ln2_temp: Scalar { value: '300', unit: 'kelvin' })
(ln2_boltzmann: Constant { name: 'k_B', value: '1.380649e-23', unit: 'J/K' })
(ln2_cost: Metric {
  name: 'landauer_bound', formula: 'k_B * T * ln(2)',
  value: '2.867e-21', unit: 'joules',
  note: 'minimum energy to VENT one bit at 300K'
})

(ln2_temp | ln2_boltzmann)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'multiply' }]->(ln2_kt: Scalar { value: '4.14195e-21' })
(ln2_kt)-[:VENT { cost: 'ln(2)' }]->(ln2_cost)

// Half-life: time for half the state to be vented
(ln2_halflife: Metric { name: 'half_life', formula: 'ln(2) / lambda', note: 'VENT duration for 50% reduction' })

// Conversion rate: log_phi(2) = 1.44042 Fibonacci steps per doubling
(ln2_phi_conv: Ratio {
  name: 'log_phi_2', value: '1.44042', formula: 'ln(2) / ln(phi)',
  note: 'Fibonacci steps per doubling -- SLIVER to VENT conversion'
})

(ln2_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'ln(2) is VENT quantum: Landauer minimum cost of forgetting one bit',
  status: 'PROVED'
})


// ============================================================================
// VII. Feigenbaum delta = 4.66920... and alpha = 2.50290...
//      THE TRANSITION CONSTANTS -- Status: REFRAMED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: delta and alpha govern period-doubling route to chaos -- the
// transition from NON-LINEAR to POST-LINEAR.  delta = 4.669: rate at which
// bifurcations accelerate.  alpha = 2.503: attractor scaling at each
// bifurcation.  Together they describe how primitives break down: FOLD/RACE
// become unstable, FORK cascades, SLIVER creates fractals, VENT unbounds.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL: If delta were rational, approach to chaos would be periodic
// -- you would reach chaos and return.  Irrationality ensures the transition
// is genuinely asymptotic.  (Whether delta/alpha are algebraic or
// transcendental remains open.)
//
// PHI CONNECTION: delta / phi^3 = 4.669 / 4.236 = 1.102... ~ 1.
// alpha / phi^2 = 2.502 / 2.618 = 0.956... ~ 1.  The Feigenbaum constants
// live in the "phi neighborhood" -- CONJECTURED.

(feigen_delta: Constant {
  name: 'feigenbaum_delta', value: '4.66920160910',
  formula: 'lim r(n+1)/r(n) in period doubling',
  primitive: 'TRANSITION', role: 'rate', status: 'REFRAMED'
})
(feigen_alpha: Constant {
  name: 'feigenbaum_alpha', value: '2.50290787510',
  formula: 'attractor scaling at bifurcation',
  primitive: 'TRANSITION', role: 'geometry', status: 'REFRAMED'
})

// Period doubling cascade: FOLD becomes unstable
(feigen_p1: State { period: '1', regime: 'LINEAR' })
(feigen_p2: State { period: '2', regime: 'NON-LINEAR' })
(feigen_p4: State { period: '4', regime: 'NON-LINEAR' })
(feigen_p8: State { period: '8', regime: 'NON-LINEAR' })
(feigen_chaos: State { period: 'inf', regime: 'POST-LINEAR' })

(feigen_p1)-[:PROCESS { bifurcation: '1' }]->(feigen_p2)
(feigen_p2)-[:PROCESS { bifurcation: '2' }]->(feigen_p4)
(feigen_p4)-[:PROCESS { bifurcation: '3' }]->(feigen_p8)
(feigen_p8)-[:PROCESS { bifurcation: 'inf' }]->(feigen_chaos)

// Bifurcation intervals shrink by delta
(feigen_r1: Metric { name: 'r1', value: '1.0' })
(feigen_r2: Metric { name: 'r2', value: '0.21417', formula: '1/delta' })
(feigen_r3: Metric { name: 'r3', value: '0.04588', formula: '1/delta^2' })

(feigen_r1)-[:VENT { rate: '1/delta' }]->(feigen_r2)
(feigen_r2)-[:VENT { rate: '1/delta' }]->(feigen_r3)

// Self-similar attractor: SLIVER at the edge of chaos
(feigen_attractor: Fractal {
  scaling: '2.50290',
  note: 'alpha governs self-similar SLIVER pattern at transition'
})

// delta ~ phi^3, alpha ~ phi^2 (CONJECTURED)
(feigen_phi3: Ratio { formula: 'delta / phi^3', value: '1.10218', note: 'three stacked interference levels' })
(feigen_phi2: Ratio { formula: 'alpha / phi^2', value: '0.95585', note: 'two stacked interference levels' })

(feigen_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'Feigenbaum constants govern TRANSITION: period-doubling to chaos',
  status: 'REFRAMED'
})


// ============================================================================
// VIII. Euler-Mascheroni gamma = 0.57721566...
//       THE ACCUMULATION CONSTANT -- Status: CONJECTURED
// ============================================================================
//
// WHAT: gamma = lim(H(n) - ln(n)) where H(n) = 1 + 1/2 + ... + 1/n.
// The harmonic series is the simplest FOLD without VENT: every term is
// kept, nothing shed, sum diverges.  gamma measures divergence rate --
// what happens when FOLD runs without its complement.
// Appears in: Riemann zeta, digamma, coupon collector, Mertens' theorem.
//
// WHY IRRATIONAL (CONJECTURED -- open problem): If gamma were rational,
// FOLD-without-VENT would be reducible to a finite expression.  The
// conjecture that gamma is irrational reflects the belief that accumulation
// without shedding is genuinely irreducible.
//
// PHI CONNECTION: gamma / ln(phi) = 0.577 / 0.481 = 1.199 ~ 6/5.
// gamma < ln(phi) < ln(2): accumulation constant < interference log < vent
// quantum.  Pure accumulation is weaker than either interference or venting.

(gamma_source: Constant {
  name: 'euler_mascheroni_gamma', value: '0.57721566490',
  formula: 'lim(H(n) - ln(n)) as n -> inf',
  primitive: 'FOLD', role: 'accumulation', status: 'CONJECTURED'
})

// Harmonic series: FOLD without VENT
(gamma_t1: Scalar { value: '1.0', label: '1/1' })
(gamma_t2: Scalar { value: '0.5', label: '1/2' })
(gamma_t3: Scalar { value: '0.333', label: '1/3' })
(gamma_t4: Scalar { value: '0.25', label: '1/4' })
(gamma_t5: Scalar { value: '0.2', label: '1/5' })
(gamma_t6: Scalar { value: '0.167', label: '1/6' })

(gamma_sum: Metric { name: 'H(6)', value: '2.45', note: 'harmonic partial sum -- diverges without VENT' })
(gamma_t1 | gamma_t2 | gamma_t3 | gamma_t4 | gamma_t5 | gamma_t6)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'sum', vent: 'none' }]->(gamma_sum)

// gamma = H(n) - ln(n) as n -> inf
(gamma_ln6: Metric { name: 'ln(6)', value: '1.79176' })
(gamma_diff: Metric {
  name: 'gamma_approx', value: '0.65824',
  note: 'H(6) - ln(6) = 0.658 -- converges to gamma = 0.577 slowly'
})
(gamma_sum | gamma_ln6)-[:FOLD { strategy: 'subtract' }]->(gamma_diff)

// FOLD with VENT vs without: convergence vs divergence
(gamma_comparison: Comparison {
  fold_with_vent: 'Fibonacci ratio converges to phi = 1.618',
  fold_without_vent: 'harmonic sum diverges, excess = gamma = 0.577',
  note: 'gamma measures the cost of absent VENT'
})

// Coupon collector: expected RACE time involves gamma
(gamma_coupon: Metric {
  name: 'coupon_collector', formula: 'n * H(n) ~ n * (ln(n) + gamma)',
  note: 'expected time to complete n-way RACE ~ n*ln(n) + n*gamma'
})

(gamma_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'gamma measures FOLD without VENT: harmonic accumulation divergence',
  status: 'CONJECTURED'
})


// ============================================================================
// IX. SYNTHESIS -- THE PERIODIC TABLE OF IRRATIONALS
// ============================================================================
//
//   Constant    Value       Primitive     Role              Status
//   ----------  ----------  -----------   ----------------  ----------
//   phi         1.61803     SLIVER     eigenvalue        PROVED
//   sqrt(2)     1.41421     FOLD          symmetric merge   REFRAMED
//   sqrt(3)     1.73205     RACE          equilateral sym   CONJECTURED
//   e           2.71828     VENT          decay base        REFRAMED
//   pi          3.14159     FORK          radial period     REFRAMED
//   ln(2)       0.69315     VENT          quantum           PROVED
//   delta       4.66920     TRANSITION    doubling rate     REFRAMED
//   alpha       2.50291     TRANSITION    attractor scale   REFRAMED
//   gamma       0.57722     FOLD          accumulation      CONJECTURED
//
// The algebraic/transcendental boundary (sqrt(3) -> e) corresponds to
// finite-arity operations -> continuous operations.  CONJECTURED.
//
// Cross-constant relationships:
//   e^phi       = 5.043  ~ 5 (number of primitives)          CONJECTURED
//   pi/phi      = 1.942  ~ 2 (FORK/SLIVER ratio)          CONJECTURED
//   delta/phi^3 = 1.102  ~ 1 (transition ~ 3x interference)  CONJECTURED
//   alpha/phi^2 = 0.956  ~ 1 (attractor ~ 2x interference)   CONJECTURED
//   ln(2)/ln(phi) = 1.440 (VENT-quantum/SLIVER conversion) PROVED
//   sqrt(3)/phi = 1.070  ~ 1 (RACE ~ SLIVER at 3-arity)   CONJECTURED

(periodic_table: Topology { name: 'periodic-table-of-irrationals' })

// Primary constants -- one per primitive
(pt_phi: Entry { constant: 'phi', value: '1.618', primitive: 'SLIVER', class: 'algebraic' })
(pt_sqrt2: Entry { constant: 'sqrt(2)', value: '1.414', primitive: 'FOLD', class: 'algebraic' })
(pt_sqrt3: Entry { constant: 'sqrt(3)', value: '1.732', primitive: 'RACE', class: 'algebraic' })
(pt_e: Entry { constant: 'e', value: '2.718', primitive: 'VENT', class: 'transcendental' })
(pt_pi: Entry { constant: 'pi', value: '3.141', primitive: 'FORK', class: 'transcendental' })

// Secondary constants
(pt_ln2: Entry { constant: 'ln(2)', value: '0.693', primitive: 'VENT', role: 'quantum', class: 'transcendental' })
(pt_gamma: Entry { constant: 'gamma', value: '0.577', primitive: 'FOLD', role: 'accumulation', class: 'unknown' })

// Transition constants
(pt_delta: Entry { constant: 'delta', value: '4.669', primitive: 'TRANSITION', role: 'rate', class: 'unknown' })
(pt_alpha: Entry { constant: 'alpha', value: '2.503', primitive: 'TRANSITION', role: 'geometry', class: 'unknown' })

// Ordering topology: constants ordered by value
(pt_gamma)-[:PROCESS { order: '1' }]->(pt_ln2)
(pt_ln2)-[:PROCESS { order: '2' }]->(pt_sqrt2)
(pt_sqrt2)-[:PROCESS { order: '3' }]->(pt_phi)
(pt_phi)-[:PROCESS { order: '4' }]->(pt_sqrt3)
(pt_sqrt3)-[:PROCESS { order: '5' }]->(pt_alpha)
(pt_alpha)-[:PROCESS { order: '6' }]->(pt_e)
(pt_e)-[:PROCESS { order: '7' }]->(pt_pi)
(pt_pi)-[:PROCESS { order: '8' }]->(pt_delta)

// Algebraic-to-transcendental boundary
(pt_sqrt3)-[:PROCESS { note: 'algebraic/transcendental boundary' }]->(pt_e)

// Cross-relationships via SLIVER
(pt_phi)-[:SLIVER { mode: 'constructive', product: 'e^phi ~ 5' }]->(pt_e)
(pt_phi)-[:SLIVER { mode: 'constructive', product: 'pi/phi ~ 2' }]->(pt_pi)
(pt_sqrt2)-[:SLIVER { mode: 'constructive', product: 'sqrt(6)' }]->(pt_sqrt3)

(periodic_table)-[:FORK]->(pt_phi | pt_sqrt2 | pt_sqrt3 | pt_e | pt_pi | pt_ln2 | pt_gamma | pt_delta | pt_alpha)


// ============================================================================
// X. VERIFICATION HARNESS
// ============================================================================

(table_verify: Verify {
  claim: 'periodic table orders and relates the named irrationals',
  status: 'REFRAMED'
})

(test_suite)-[:PROCESS]->(phi_verify | pi_verify | e_verify | sqrt2_verify | sqrt3_verify | ln2_verify | feigen_verify | gamma_verify | table_verify)

(phi_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(phi_result: Result)
(pi_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(pi_result: Result)
(e_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(e_result: Result)
(sqrt2_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(sqrt2_result: Result)
(sqrt3_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(sqrt3_result: Result)
(ln2_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(ln2_result: Result)
(feigen_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(feigen_result: Result)
(gamma_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(gamma_result: Result)
(table_verify)-[:PROCESS { expect: 'safe' }]->(table_result: Result)

(phi_result | pi_result | e_result | sqrt2_result | sqrt3_result | ln2_result | feigen_result | gamma_result | table_result)-[:PROCESS { strategy: 'all-pass' }]->(verdict: Verdict)


// ============================================================================
// XI. OPEN QUESTIONS
// ============================================================================
//
// 1. Is the ordering FOLD < SLIVER < RACE < VENT < FORK deep or
//    coincidental?  Algebraic/transcendental split correlates with
//    finite-arity vs continuous-arity.  CONJECTURED.
//
// 2. Is gamma irrational?  Major open problem.  If rational, FOLD-without-
//    VENT has a closed form and the framework needs revision.  OPEN.
//
// 3. Are the Feigenbaum constants transcendental?  Determines whether
//    transition is as complex as the continuous primitives.  OPEN.
//
// 4. Is e^phi exactly 5?  No (5.04316...) but proximity to the number
//    of primitives is suggestive.  NUMEROLOGICAL.
//
// 5. Does continued-fraction complexity mirror primitive complexity?
//    phi = [1;1,1,...] simplest; e = [2;1,2,1,1,4,...]; pi has no
//    pattern.  SLIVER < VENT < FORK in CF complexity?  CONJECTURED.
(verdict)-[:MEASURE { reason: 'topology-audit' }]->(irrational_constants_test_gg_trace:Trace)
